{"parse":{"title":"Porphyrogeniture","pageid":38908122,"revid":676549078,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Porphyrogeniture</b>, also sometimes referred to as <b>born to the purple</b>, is a system of political succession that favours the rights of sons born after their father has become king or emperor, over older siblings born before their father's ascent to the throne.\n</p><p>Examples of this practice include <a href=\"/wiki/Byzantium\" title=\"Byzantium\">Byzantium</a> and the <a href=\"/wiki/Nupe_Kingdom\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Nupe Kingdom\">Nupe Kingdom</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> In late 11th century England and Normandy, the theory of porphyrogeniture was used by <a href=\"/wiki/Henry_I_of_England\" title=\"Henry I of England\">Henry I of England</a> to justify why he, and not his older brother <a href=\"/wiki/Robert_Curthose\" title=\"Robert Curthose\">Robert Curthose</a>, should inherit the throne after the death of their brother <a href=\"/wiki/William_Rufus\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"William Rufus\">William Rufus</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Porphyrogeniture&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Porphyrogennetos\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Porphyrogennetos\">Porphyrogennetos</a> - honorific title given to a son</li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Born_in_the_purple\" title=\"Born in the purple\">Born in the purple</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Porphyrogeniture&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<dl><dt>References</dt></dl>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Goody, p.33.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Hollister, p. 105.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<dl><dt>Bibliography</dt></dl>\n<ul><li><cite id=\"CITEREFGoody1979\" class=\"citation book\">Goody, Jack (1979). \"Introduction\".  In Goody, Jack. <i>Succession to High Office</i>. Cambridge, UK: Cambridge University Press. pp.&#160;1\u201356. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780521297325\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9780521297325\">9780521297325</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=Introduction&amp;rft.btitle=Succession+to+High+Office&amp;rft.place=Cambridge%2C+UK&amp;rft.pages=1-56&amp;rft.pub=Cambridge+University+Press&amp;rft.date=1979&amp;rft.isbn=9780521297325&amp;rft.aulast=Goody&amp;rft.aufirst=Jack&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APorphyrogeniture\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite id=\"CITEREFHollister2003\" class=\"citation book\">Hollister, C. Warren (2003). <i>Henry I</i>. New Haven, US and London, UK: Yale University Press. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780300098297\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9780300098297\">9780300098297</a>.</cite><